----Python Syntax----
Python syntax is like the set of rules that tell you how to write instructions in Python so the computer can understand and follow them. Think of it as the grammar and spelling rules in English that help people communicate clearly. In Python, the syntax is designed to be simple and close to everyday English, which makes it easier for beginners to learn and write code without getting confused by complicated symbols or structures.

For example, to print a message on the screen, you write:
print("Hello, world!")

This line tells the computer to show the words "Hello, world!" Just like a sentence in English, it starts with a command (print), followed by what you want to print inside parentheses and quotes. Python uses indentation (spaces at the beginning of a line) to organize code blocks, which is like using paragraphs in writing to separate ideas clearly.

Python syntax means the rules used to write Python programs correctly.

Basic Rules of Python Syntax :-
   1. Python is case-sensitive (name and Name are different).
   2. No semicolon (;) is required at the end of lines.
   3. Indentation (spaces/tabs) is important in Python.
   4. Statements are written line by line.
   5. Variables are created without declaring data type.
   6. Comments are written using #.

Think about white space like the spaces between words in a sentence—they help make things clear but don't change the meaning. In Python, extra spaces around symbols like plus signs don't cause problems. But if you split a command across lines without telling Python it's continuing, it gets confused. You can use a backslash / at the end of a line to say, "Hey, this command isn't finished yet!" 

----Whitespace in Python is important because:----
    •	Code Structure   : Python uses indentation (a type of whitespace) to define blocks of code, like the body of an if statement or a                          loop. This tells Python which lines belong together logically.
    •	Readability      : Proper use of spaces and indentation makes your code easier for humans to read and understand. It visually                              separates different parts of the code.
    •	Avoiding Errors  : Incorrect or missing indentation causes Python to raise errors, so consistent whitespace helps your code run                            correctly.
In short, whitespace in Python is not just for looks—it’s a key part of how the language understands your program. 

----indentation----
indentation is like the paragraphs in your letter. It shows which parts belong together. For example, in an "if" statement, the code inside needs to be indented so Python knows it's part of that condition. If you forget to indent, Python will give you an error because it expects that indentation to understand your code's structure.
    •	The code that should run only if the condition is true must be indented (usually by 4 spaces) on the next line(s).
    •	This indentation tells Python that these indented lines are part of the if block.
    •	If you don't indent, Python will give an "IndentationError" because it expects an indented block after the if statement.

